🔍 Part 1: Decomposition — The Art of "Peeling the Onion"

What it is:
Breaking a complex problem into smaller, independent parts that you can solve one at a time.

Ethiopian Farm-to-Market Example:

Big Problem: "Farmers lose too much harvest before selling."

Let’s peel the onion layer by layer:

Layer

	

Question

	

Insight




Layer 1

	

Where exactly does loss happen?

	

During transport (35%), at collection points (25%), in storage (40%)




Layer 2

	

Why does transport loss happen?

	

Bad roads → tomatoes crushed; no cooling → onions sprout




Layer 3

	

Why no cooling?

	

Refrigerated trucks cost $25,000—too expensive for cooperatives




Layer 4

	

What’s affordable?

	

Clay pot evaporative coolers ($5/unit) used in Sudan

👉 Your move: Solve Layer 4 first. Not the whole chain—just one piece that unlocks the next.

💡 Golden Rule: "Solve the smallest piece that creates the biggest ripple."

🔍 Part 2: Abstraction — The Skill of "Zooming In & Out"

What it is:
Deciding which details matter for this specific problem—and safely ignoring the rest.

Try This Exercise:
Draw a map from your village to the nearest market. Now answer:

❌ Too much detail: "Turn left after the third mango tree with the broken branch near Mama Aisha’s compound where her goat always sleeps..."
✅ Just right: "Turn left at the blue mosque → straight 500m → market entrance on right"

In Software:
When building a farm logistics app, you need:

✅ Farmer location (GPS coordinates)
✅ Crop type & quantity
✅ Road condition rating (good/fair/poor)
❌ Farmer’s birthdate, favorite football team, or number of goats (unless relevant to credit scoring!)

💡 Golden Rule: "Abstraction isn’t ignoring reality—it’s respecting your user’s attention."

🌍 African Wisdom Corner

In many African cultures, elders solve disputes by decomposing the conflict:

"First, let’s hear from the farmer. Then the herder. Then the chief. We will not mix all voices at once."

And they abstract by focusing on restoration—not blame:

"We don’t care who threw the first stone. We care: How do we share this land so both families eat next season?"

This is computational thinking—long before computers existed.

✍️ Let’s Practice: The "Matatu Scheduling Problem"

Scenario:
In Nairobi, matatus (minibuses) crowd the city center during rush hour—but suburbs have empty vehicles. Passengers wait 40+ minutes. Drivers earn less.

Your 15-Minute Challenge:

Decompose this into 4 smaller problems (e.g., "Drivers don’t know where passengers are waiting")
Abstract a matatu ride down to 5 essential data points (e.g., route ID, current location, seats available...)
Sketch a simple system diagram showing how these pieces connect

💬 Work in pairs. No computers—just paper, pens, and your brilliant minds.

